                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The handwriting is characterized by rounded and right-sloping letters. The quality often changes throughout the Ms. (s., e.g., on fol. 102r, column a and columns bc).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic">
Some distinctive features:<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic">
- ብ and ኵ have the 6th order marker very close to the top of the letter (e.g., fols. 53ra l.7, l.13, 108ra l.2);<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic">
- the upper horizontal strokes of the letters መ and ወ are slightly slanted to the left;<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic">
- ፪ has the bottom loop open (e.g, fol. 51va);<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h7" script="Ethiopic">
- ፮ has sometimes the loop open, looking like “compressed” ፯ (s. the sixth hour of the days: e.g., fols. 26rb, 51vb);<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h8" script="Ethiopic">
- usually, the numerals are written with double dashes above and below (s., e.g., fols. 27rb, 30rc);<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h9" script="Ethiopic">
- in many words, the 3rd order is written instead of the 5th (?).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
